# Plan: Add Pagination to GET /users

## Context
The `GET /users` endpoint currently returns all 15 users as a flat JSON array (`res.json(users)`).
The goal is to add `page` / `limit` query-parameter pagination and return a structured response
shape that the already-written test suite in `tests/routes.test.ts` expects.

---

## Files to Modify

| File | Change |
|------|--------|
| `src/routes.ts` | Rewrite the `GET /users` handler to paginate and return the new shape |
| `src/types.ts` | Add a `PaginatedResponse<T>` interface (optional but keeps things tidy) |

No changes needed to `src/data.ts`, `src/app.ts`, or any test files.

---

## Step-by-Step Implementation

### Step 1 — Add `PaginatedResponse` type to `src/types.ts`

Append after the existing `User` interface:

```typescript
export interface PaginationMeta {
  page: number;
  limit: number;
  total: number;
  totalPages: number;
}

export interface PaginatedResponse<T> {
  data: T[];
  pagination: PaginationMeta;
}
```

### Step 2 — Rewrite the `GET /users` handler in `src/routes.ts`

Replace the current simple handler:

```typescript
// GET /users - returns all users
router.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  res.json(users);
});
```

With the paginated version:

```typescript
// GET /users - returns paginated users
router.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  const page  = Math.max(1, parseInt(req.query.page  as string, 10) || 1);
  const limit = Math.max(1, parseInt(req.query.limit as string, 10) || 10);

  const total      = users.length;
  const totalPages = Math.ceil(total / limit);
  const start      = (page - 1) * limit;
  const data       = users.slice(start, start + limit);   // empty array when out-of-range

  res.json({
    data,
    pagination: { page, limit, total, totalPages },
  });
});
```

Key details:
- `parseInt(...) || 1` / `|| 10` handles `NaN` (non-numeric strings) by falling back to defaults.
- `Math.max(1, ...)` prevents page/limit ≤ 0.
- `Array.prototype.slice` returns `[]` when `start >= total`, satisfying the out-of-range requirement.
- `totalPages` uses `Math.ceil` so 15 items / 10 per page = **2**, and 15 / 5 = **3**.

---

## Existing Tests That Must Keep Passing (no changes required)

All 6 tests in `tests/routes.test.ts` are already written for the new paginated shape:

| Test | Validates |
|------|-----------|
| Default page & limit | `data.length === 10`, `pagination.total === 15`, `totalPages === 2` |
| Second page | `data.length === 5`, `pagination.page === 2` |
| Custom limit=5 | `data.length === 5`, `pagination.totalPages === 3` |
| Out-of-range page=100 | `data === []`, `pagination.page === 100`, status 200 |
| GET /users/:id (existing) | Status 200, correct name |
| GET /users/999 (existing) | Status 404 |

---

## Verification

Run the test suite:
```bash
npm test
```

Expected: all 6 tests green, 0 failures.

